we became reconnected to our natural life. Before, we the people of Maldives might not have understood what a coral reef is or what is a mangrove forest, but now we have understood that we need to preserve it. The truth is we are in a position where we want to put value and preserve it instead of destroying it.

Like I said we are the have-and-have-nots of the world the islands of Maldives are made up of sand and coral and sand and coral cannot last forever. Sand and coral, over time will change forms and maybe one day there will be nothing left. We need to do something about it.

We have done something about it. We also have put restrictions where nobody can set foot on some of these islands. From the time the project to build the biggest boating tourism project in the world by ETE was proposed to the ETE officials, the Maldivian Government, local and international conservation organizations, NGOs, fisherman associations, stakeholders and investors, we are one and the same when it comes to Maldivian environmental conservation. The series of worldwide negative media coverage about ETE by the travel publication, blogs and reporters were also discussed with all of them during the Maldives Alliance for Responsible Tourism conference, we have been working alongside each other on many other issues. Today those who are negative about this project, are quite happy with every step that has happened over the past year.
